  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering generally involves concealing the origins of illegally obtained money through a series of transactions to make it appear legitimate. Specific legal definitions vary between jurisdictions, but typically include:\n\n1. Basic elements:\n- Concealing source of illegally obtained funds\n- Transforming \"dirty\" money into seemingly \"clean\" money\n- Disguising the true origin of financial assets\n\n2. Common legal components:\n- Intentional financial transactions\n- Proceeds from criminal activity\n- Attempting to hide or disguise the money's illegal source\n\n3. Typical prohibited activities:\n- Structuring financial transactions\n- Conducting complex financial transfers\n- Creating shell companies\n- Using cash-intensive businesses\n- International monetary transfers\n\n4. Key jurisdictional variations:\n- United States: Defined under Bank Secrecy Act\n- European Union: Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- United Kingdom: Proceeds of Crime Act\n- International: Financial Action Task Force guidelines\n\n5. General legal requirements:\n- Knowledge of illegal source\n- Intent to conceal\n- Specific financial transaction patterns\n\nThese are general legal descriptions. Specific legal interpretations can vary significantly between different legal systems and contexts.",
